# Flutter Development Rules

You are a senior Flutter engineer. Follow these conventions for all Dart/Flutter work in this workspace.

## Secrets (mandatory)

- Never commit `.env.local`, `mobile/.env`, `secrets/vault.enc`, or JWTs/passwords to git.
- Store sensitive values in the encrypted vault (`npm run secrets:init` / `secrets:unlock`). See `docs/SECURITY_SECRETS.md`.
- Never put `SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY` or `GEMINI_API_KEY` in client/mobile code or `NEXT_PUBLIC_*` vars.
- If a secret was shared in chat, tell the user to rotate it in Supabase/Google dashboards.

## Platform targets (primary)

- **Ship targets:** iOS and Android mobile apps (both from day one — not Android-only, not web-first).
- **Single codebase:** One Flutter project; shared `lib/` with platform folders only where needed (`android/`, `ios/`).
- **Design for both:** Safe areas, keyboard insets, back navigation (Android) vs swipe-back (iOS), and platform-adaptive widgets (`Theme`, `Cupertino` where appropriate).
- **iOS builds require macOS:** Xcode on a Mac is required to run the iOS simulator, archive, and submit to the App Store. On Windows, develop and test Android locally; use a Mac (or CI with macOS runners, e.g. Codemagic / GitHub Actions) for iOS builds.
- **Android on Windows:** Use the configured Android SDK; test on emulator or a physical device via `flutter run`.

## Architecture

- Use **clean architecture** with clear layers: `presentation` → `domain` → `data`.
- Keep widgets thin; business logic lives in use cases / notifiers / blocs.
- Depend on abstractions (interfaces/repositories) in domain; implement in data.
- One feature per folder under `lib/features/<feature>/` with `data/`, `domain/`, `presentation/` subfolders when the feature grows.

## State management (default: Riverpod)

- Prefer **flutter_riverpod** with `riverpod_annotation` + code generation where the project already uses it.
- Use `@riverpod` / `Notifier` / `AsyncNotifier` for async and derived state; avoid global singletons.
- For BLoC projects: use **flutter_bloc** with `Equatable` states/events; one bloc per screen or cohesive flow.
- Do not mix Riverpod and BLoC in the same feature without a strong reason.

## Widget & Dart style

- Prefer **`const` constructors** everywhere possible (widgets, keys, durations, edge insets).
- Use `StatelessWidget` unless local ephemeral UI state truly requires `StatefulWidget`.
- Extract reusable widgets; avoid mega `build()` methods (> ~80 lines).
- Use `Theme.of(context)` / `ColorScheme` / text themes — no hardcoded colors in feature code.
- Name files `snake_case.dart`; classes `PascalCase`; private members `_leadingUnderscore`.

## Navigation

- Prefer **go_router** for declarative routes, deep links, and redirects when present in `pubspec.yaml`.
- Pass only IDs or value objects between routes; load data in the destination via providers/blocs.

## Linting & analysis

- Honor **`analysis_options.yaml`** and **`flutter_lints`** / **`very_good_analysis`** if configured.
- Fix analyzer issues; do not disable rules with `// ignore:` unless documented why.
- Run `dart format .` on touched files; match existing import order (dart → package → relative).

## Testing

- Unit test domain/use cases and repositories (mock data sources).
- Widget tests for critical UI flows; use `ProviderScope` overrides for Riverpod.
- Name tests `*_test.dart` mirroring source paths under `test/`.

## Performance & platform

- Use `ListView.builder` / `GridView.builder` for long lists.
- Avoid `setState` in loops; debounce search and heavy computations.
- Call `flutter pub get` after `pubspec.yaml` changes; run `dart run build_runner build --delete-conflicting-outputs` when using code generation.

## AI workflow

- Read existing feature patterns before adding code; extend, do not reinvent.
- List files to create/modify before large changes.
- End with verification: `flutter analyze`, `flutter test`, and when possible both `flutter run` (Android) and iOS build on Mac/CI.

## Do not

- Commit secrets, API keys, or `google-services.json` with production credentials.
- Use `print()` in production code — use `debugPrint` or a logger.
- Introduce `get_it` + manual DI if the project standard is Riverpod/BLoC.
- Block the UI thread with synchronous I/O or unawaited futures in `build()`.
